to speak. What happened?

614
00:55:19,400 --> 00:55:22,198
Well, I heard this thundering
great crash upstairs,

615
00:55:22,400 --> 00:55:25,233
and thinking it was
that damned cat, up I went.

616
00:55:25,440 --> 00:55:27,829
If I've shooed that cat out once,
I've shooed him out...

617
00:55:28,040 --> 00:55:29,393
Get on with it.

618
00:55:29,600 --> 00:55:32,956
Well, there she was, lying beside
the bed... Mrs Leamington, this is.

619
00:55:33,160 --> 00:55:36,391
...with one of her medical books
on the floor where she'd dropped it.

620
00:55:36,600 --> 00:55:39,797
All blue, her face was...
Doris, don't go into it.

621
00:55:40,000 --> 00:55:41,479
Did you fetch the doctor?
Yes.

622
00:55:41,680 --> 00:55:45,116
He said she was dead
straight away. I helped him
to lift her onto the bed.

623
00:55:45,320 --> 00:55:47,231
Oh, she does look awful.

624
00:55:47,760 --> 00:55:48,795
[KNOCKING]

625
00:55:49,000 --> 00:55:50,399
Come in.

626
00:55:50,600 --> 00:55:53,717
My apologies for that, sir.
Doris is not herself.

627
00:55:54,600 --> 00:55:57,990
Your wife is at peace,
Mr James. It was a quick
and merciful release.

628
00:55:58,280 --> 00:55:59,838
[***]

629
00:56:00,440 --> 00:56:04,274
I don't suppose she knew what hit her.
Something hit her?

630
00:56:04,640 --> 00:56:08,758
Pardon?
Oh, I... I see.

631
00:56:10,800 --> 00:56:14,270
What do we do?
I'll take care of everything, Mr James.

632
00:56:14,480 --> 00:56:18,029
You're... You're too overcome
with grief and shock.

633
00:56:18,240 --> 00:56:20,151
Yes, that's right.

634
00:56:21,960 --> 00:56:24,872
No doubt you'd like to pay
your last respects?

635
00:58:00,040 --> 00:58:02,838
It was nice of you to come,
Georgy.

636
00:58:03,040 --> 00:58:05,793
Oh, I don't mind funerals.

637
00:58:14,800 --> 00:58:17,394
JOS:
Oh. That's lovely, Georgy. Yes.

638
00:58:19,600 --> 00:58:20,555
Look, feet.

639
